    <title>Dihedral groups</title>
<subsection xml:id="ss_isometries">
<title>Isometries of <m>\R^n</m></title>
<definition xml:id="d_isom">
    
 <title>Isometry</title>
 <notation>
        <usage><m>\Isom(\R^n)</m></usage>
      <description>isometries of <m>\R^n</m></description>
    </notation>
 <statement>
 <p>
 Fix a positive integer <m>n</m>. Let <m>d</m> denote the standard Euclidean distance on <m>\R^n</m>: <ie/>, 
 <men xml:id="eq_euc_dist">
    d(\boldx, \boldy)=\sqrt{\sum_{i=1}^n(x_i-y_i)^2}
 </men>,
 for all <m>n</m>-tuples <m>\boldx=(x_1,x_2,\dots, x_n)</m> and <m>\boldy=(y_1,y_2,\dots, y_n)</m>. An <term>isometry</term> (or <term>rigid motion</term>) of <m>\R^n</m> with respect to <m>d</m> is a function <m>f\colon \R^n\rightarrow \R^n</m> satisfying 
 <men xml:id="eqn_isom">
    d(f(\boldx), f(\boldy))=d(\boldx, \boldy)
 </men>
 for all <m>\boldx,\boldy\in \R^n</m>. We denote by <m>\Isom(\R^n)</m> the set of all isometries of <m>\R^n</m>. 
 </p>
 </statement>
 </definition>
<activity xml:id="spec_isom">
 <title>Group of isometries</title>
 <statement>
 <p>
 Fix a positive integer <m>n</m>. The pair <m>(\Isom(\R^n), \circ)</m> is a group, where <m>\circ</m> is function composition. 
 </p>
 </statement>
 </activity>
 <example xml:id="eg_isometries">
 <title>Isometries</title>
 <statement>
 <p>
 Fix a positive integer <m>n</m>. Investigate the claim that <m>\Isom(\R^n)</m> is a group with respect to composition. In more detail:  
