<subsection xml:id="ss_group_presentation">
<title>Group presentations</title>
<p>
    As we saw above, the relations 
    <md>
        <mrow>r^n \amp =s^2=e \amp sr\amp= r^{-1}s=r^{n-1}s</mrow>
    </md>
    together with the fact that <m>D_n=\{r^is^j\mid 0\leq i\leq n-1, 0\leq j\leq 1\}</m> are essentially all we need to know to be able to do computations in the dihedral group <m>D_n</m>. <em>Group presentation</em> notation gives us a nice way of summarizing this defining properties. A group presentation of <m>D_n</m> is 
    <me>
        \angvec{r,s\mid r^n=s^2=e, sr=r^{-1}s}
    </me>.
    Although we introduce the notation here as a convenient way to summarize how an established group, namely <m>D_n</m>, is <q>generated</q> by the elements <m>r</m> and <m>s</m>, the notation can also be used to construct groups from scratch. Put another way, any presentation like the one above can be shown to be the presentation of an actual existing group. For example, the presentation 
    <me>
        \angvec{r,s\mid r^2=s^2=(rs)^2=e}
    </me>
    can be shown to be the define a certain group <m>G</m> of cardinality <m>4</m>. As it turns out, to make good sense of this construction, a significant amount of theory must be mobilized. As such, we will be careful to confine ourselves to using the presentation notation only to as a summary description of a group we know already to exist. The <em>quaternion group</em> below is a good example of this. 
</p>
<activity xml:id="spec_quaternion">
<title>Quaternion group</title>
<notation>
    <usage><m>Q_8</m></usage>
  <description>the quaternion group</description>
</notation>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>Q_8=\{1,-1,i,-i,j,-j,k,-k\}</m>. The following rules define a binary operation <m>\cdot</m> on <m>Q_8</m>.
<md>
    <mrow> 1\cdot a  =a\cdot 1\amp =a \text{ for all } a\in Q_8</mrow>
    <mrow>(-1)\cdot (-1) \amp =1 \amp (-1)\cdot a\amp=a\cdot (-1)=-a \text{ for all } a\in Q_8</mrow>
    <mrow>i^2  =j^2=k^2 \amp=-1</mrow>
    <mrow>ij \amp =k \amp ji\amp =-k</mrow>
    <mrow>jk \amp = i \amp kj\amp =-i</mrow>
    <mrow>ki \amp = j \amp ik\amp =-j</mrow>
</md>.
 The pair <m>(Q_8,\cdot)</m> is a group called the <term>quaternion group</term>. We have the following presentation of <m>Q_8</m>: 
 <me>
    Q_8=\angvec{i,j\mid i^2=j^2, ji=i^{-1}j}
 </me>.
</p>
</statement>
</activity>

